# TypeScript: Use `type` instead of `interface`

Always use `type` for type definitions, not `interface`. This provides consistency and flexibility across the codebase.

## Rule

- Use `type` for all type definitions (props, data models, etc.)
- Do not use `interface` unless there's an explicit need for declaration merging
- This applies to all TypeScript files across the project

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
interface EventCardProps {
  event: Event;
  onCardClick?: (eventId: string) => void;
}

// ✅ GOOD
type EventCardProps = {
  event: Event;
  onCardClick?: (eventId: string) => void;
};
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

// ✅ GOOD
type User = {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
};
```
